<br>
**********<br>
<br>
Kyonae undressed and slipped into the bath.  The water was deliciously cold and brought sharpness back to her senses.  She began to wash her wounds and cuts clean when she heard the steady pace of Naomi's staff leading into the bathroom and closing the door.<br>
<br>
&quot;Are you alright, Kyonae?&quot; she asked, setting down her staff as she sat down on an old wheelchair that had been left there by Cedric's grandmother.  <br>
<br>
Kyonae nodded, cleansing the dirt out of a grisly gash in her shoulder.  She did not mind Naomi seeing her this way, being a fellow female, and truthfully she considered her a sister.  A wiser, silent, cynical sister.  Besides, years of warrior mage instincts had taught her not to be ashamed of being unclothed in front of others...privacy was a luxury not always enjoyed.  As she washed the wounds clean, she whispered gentle spells, welding them together instantly.  &quot;Yes.  Why?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I was merely curious.  Iaret poison is very toxic.  If he had gotten you...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;...I would not be here, Naomi,&quot; she finished, sealing a long scratch along her neck.  &quot;I was fortunate.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;That you were.  But forgive me.  I digress.&quot;  Naomi made eye contact with her.  &quot;I have come to talk to you about Mirak.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I know what you would say,&quot; Kyonae said, washing the blood out of her hair.  &quot;And I'm not saying you're wrong.  But whether we can trust him or not is not an issue.  He agreed to come with us, to destroy Artema.  I have no doubt it is for his own advantage.  But we need help...and he has done nothing to prove himself treacherous.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Kyonae,&quot; Naomi said gently.  &quot;I just wish to say that you should be wary.  He has the right to know about Evil.  He has the right to know about the Falcon, and he has every right to know about you and you being a Paladai.  But...&quot; she paused.  &quot;So does Menion.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kyonae sighed.  &quot;I know he does,&quot; she whispered, looking at her reflection in the slightly bloodied water.  &quot;But unlike Mirak...he cannot understand.  Mirak does not feel...he does not care beyond his own terms...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;And Menion does care, is that what you're saying?&quot; Naomi mused.  &quot;I agree with you.  He cares more than you think.  And maybe he wouldn't understand.  But he would try...for you.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kyonae closed her eyes to her reflection.  She felt Naomi's hand place itself on her healed shoulder, and when she opened her eyes again, Naomi's face was beside her own in the water.<br>
<br>
&quot;We are your friends, Kyonae Falcona.  We will do anything in our power to help you on this journey.  That is no trifle burden you bear, I know.  And there is not one among us who would not <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>help</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> you bear it.<br>
<br>
&quot;But you must understand...Menion is the only one among us who would try to carry it <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>for</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> you, no matter what you did.&quot;  <br>
<br>
Kyonae's eyes slid shut, burning.  Two teardrops fell into the water and blurred their reflections.<br>
<br>
